The [emerald cut diamond necklace](/emerald-cut-diamond-necklace) forces a decision most buyers don't know they're making: whether to hang the stone vertically or horizontally. That single choice — the orientation — changes how the step-cut facets behave at chest level, how large the stone reads on the body, and which setting type protects it best.

Most buyers skip straight to carat weight and price. They end up with a pendant that looks smaller than expected or a setting that leaves the stone's corners exposed to daily wear. This post fixes that.

The four reasons to go east-west, the SI1 clarity rule at pendant distance, the full step-cut tennis necklace pricing by CTW and metal, and the exact decisions to make at every budget are all here.

The emerald cut behaves differently as a pendant than any other diamond shape. A round pendant has no orientation — it is symmetrical. An oval pendant has a long axis, but the brilliant-cut facets scatter light in all directions regardless of which way it hangs. The emerald cut is a step-cut stone. Its facets are rectangular planes stacked in parallel rows. Those rows create directional light — strong bands when facing the viewer, much less effect when edge-on. Orientation is not a preference for the emerald cut pendant. It is an optical decision that changes how the stone works.

That is why the east-west choice exists in the first place. When a retailer builds an east-west emerald cut bezel pendant, they are acknowledging that the stone works better horizontally. When a buyer hangs one north-south, they are often working against the stone's primary optical feature without realizing it.

---

**TL;DR**

4 reasons east-west wins for an emerald cut diamond necklace:
1. Step-cut reflections run parallel to the collarbone — the most wearable light direction for this shape
2. East-west presents the long axis to the viewer — reads 20–30% wider at chest level than the same stone hung vertically
3. Bezel settings (standard on east-west pendants) protect the emerald cut's vulnerable corners from chipping
4. East-west is the modern orientation; north-south is traditional — orientation defines the aesthetic more than any other variable

