## The Orientation Rule

This is the framework for every emerald cut diamond necklace decision. The shape's optical identity comes from its step-cut facets. Every other choice — setting type, carat weight, chain length — comes after you decide which axis to present.

[![East-west emerald cut diamond bezel pendant necklace in white gold lifestyle shot](https://ion.bluenile.com/sets/Jewelry/Photoshoot/Bluenile/LifeStyleV4/FineJewelry/857044/857044_W_1_1600X1600.jpg)](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/necklaces/east-west-emerald-cut-bezel-diamond-pendant-in-platinum-1-ct-tw-h-i-si1-si2-item-251408?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)

**Orientation determines setting type.** East-west pendants are almost exclusively offered in bezel settings. North-south pendants are available in both solitaire (prong) and bezel designs. If you want a prong setting, north-south is your main option.

**Orientation affects how the chain length reads.** A north-south pendant creates a vertical hanging line that elongates the chest. An east-west pendant at the same chain length creates a horizontal accent — the stone widens the visual endpoint of the chain rather than extending it downward.

**Orientation affects perceived carat weight.** East-west presents the long axis to the viewer, making the stone read larger. A 1/2 ct. east-west pendant competes visually with a 3/4 ct. north-south pendant from the same viewing distance. This is a real difference that shows up in every side-by-side comparison.

