The platinum premium over 14K white gold is $280 at 1/2 ct. and $270 at 1 ct. For a pendant worn daily, that premium is worth paying — the bezel's metal lip holds its shape longer in platinum and needs less maintenance over years of wear.

Yellow gold and white gold are identical in price at every carat. Yellow gold creates more visual contrast against the step-cut's white light — the stone reads cleaner and more distinct against the warm metal. White gold reads more minimal. This is entirely a style decision.

The jump from 1/2 ct. to 3/4 ct. is $1,640 in 14K white gold ($1,820 → $3,460). The jump from 3/4 to 1 ct. is $1,730 ($3,460 → $5,190). Each step up is significant — match the carat to your budget and to what will actually be visible at chest level, not to an arbitrary number.

---

## The Pendant Clarity Exception

All the pre-made emerald cut pendants in certified market inventory are H-I color, SI1-SI2 clarity. In a ring context, SI1 in an emerald cut is often visible face-up. The open rectangular table shows inclusions that other shapes hide under brilliant-cut facets.

A pendant at the chest hangs 18 to 24 inches from a typical viewer. That is a 50–100% increase in viewing distance compared to a ring at arm's length. At 20 inches, an SI1 inclusion that would catch your eye on a ring becomes significantly harder to resolve.

The second factor is motion. A pendant swings as you move. A ring does not. When the pendant sways, the step-cut light rotates and the inclusion's visibility window is brief. The combination of greater viewing distance and constant motion means that SI1-SI2 on these pendants performs better at chest level than the same grade on a ring.

This is not permission to buy a heavily included pendant. SI2 can still show inclusions in the center of the table at pendant distances, especially at 3/4 ct. and 1 ct. where the stone is larger and individual facets are more visible. But SI1 pendants under 1/2 ct. are a genuine value — you are paying for a grade that works well at the actual viewing distance, not a ring-standard clarity you do not need.

The [1/4 ct. east-west bezel pendant at $910](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/necklaces/east-west-emerald-cut-bezel-diamond-pendant-in-14k-white-gold-1-4-ct-tw-h-i-si1-si2-item-251398?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the clearest example of this exception. At 1/4 ct. and pendant distance, SI1 inclusions are not visible in normal wear. The pendant clarity exception makes the entry-level pieces a better value than their grade label suggests.

[![East-west emerald cut bezel diamond pendant necklace worn at chest level white gold 3/4 carat](https://ion.bluenile.com/sets/Jewelry/Photoshoot/Bluenile/LifeStyle/DiamondBasics/857142/857142_EMR_1500CT_W_2_1600X1600.jpg)](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/necklaces/east-west-emerald-cut-bezel-diamond-pendant-in-14k-white-gold-3-4-ct-tw-h-i-si1-si2-item-251404?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)

