## Emerald Cut Diamond Tennis Necklace

The emerald cut diamond tennis necklace is a completely different product from a brilliant-cut tennis necklace. Most buyers do not know this until they see both in person.

Before comparing them, it helps to understand the scale. At 10 CTW, the necklace contains approximately 34–36 individual emerald cut stones, each roughly 0.28–0.30ct. They sit in a continuous east-west bezel circuit around the full collarbone. The band of metal and stone at the collarbone is wider and more structured than most buyers picture — this is a statement piece, not a subtle accent.

In a brilliant-cut tennis (round, oval), each stone scatters light in all directions at once. The necklace creates continuous sparkle from every angle. That is the image most people have of a diamond tennis necklace.

In an emerald cut tennis, each stone reflects light in long horizontal bands — the step-cut facets run parallel to the skin as each stone sits east-west in its bezel. When you move, those bands shift in unison across the entire necklace. The effect is a rolling wave of structured light, not continuous glitter. If you expect sparkle, an emerald cut tennis will surprise you. If you want architectural presence, nothing else in fine jewelry delivers it the same way.

At 10 CTW of east-west set emerald cuts, you have approximately 30–35 individual stones, each roughly 4–5mm wide, set in a continuous bezel line. The step-cut facets create a horizontal band of moving light across the collarbone — one unified optical surface rather than 35 independent sparkle points.

